properties.documentation: IDEAS Foundation : IDEAS Top Level
The IDEAS Model
Information Exchange

The IDEAS Model is a formal ontology developed to support the exchange and sharing of enterprise architectures. It has been developed by the IDEAS Group, which is a consortium of Australian, Canadian, Swedish, UK and USA defence ministries.
This model is the IDEAS Foundation. Its purpose is to provide a basic framework for expressing concepts that are frequently used in enterprise architecture. It is expected that users and implementers will extend the IDEAS Foundation for their own purposes.
The IDEAS Foundation has been used as the basis for the DoDAF 2.0 Meta-Model (DM2). The high-level IDEAS categories (Individual, Type, tuple) have also been used to categorise the elements in the UPDM (www.updm.com) domain meta-model (they even followed the IDEAS colouring scheme).
The Foundation defines the building blocks of the ontology - Types, Individuals, and tuples (relationships). These building blocks are then used as the fundamental "language" of IDEAS - i.e. all other elements are defined in terms the Foundation elements.
The IDEAS Website is http://www.ideasgroup.org
To get started, we recommend you first read the diagram conventions, as the IDEAS ontology uses UML in a slightly unusual way. Then proceed onto the IDEAS Top Level and Key Objects:
Diagram Conventions in IDEAS

The IDEAS Model is represent here in UML. The UML language is not ideally suited to ontology specification in its native form. The UML language can be extended through the use of profiles. The IDEAS Model has been developed using a UML Profile - any UML elements that are not stereotyped by one of the IDEAS foundation elements will not be considered part of an IDEAS ontology. The IDEAS Foundation specifies the fundamental types that define the profile stereotypes. The super-subtype structure in IDEAS is quite comprehensive, and showing the super-type relationships on some diagrams can result in a number of crossed lines. In these cases, supertypes of a given type will be listed in italic text in the top-right-hand corner of the UML element box.
The stereotype of an element in an IDEAS UML model is a shorthand for the element being an instance of the type refered to by the Stereotype, though the type must be one that has been defined in the root package of the foundation. Hence, if the stereotype is <<Individual>> then the element is an instance of an Individual. The following stereotyped classes, with their colour-coding are used in the model:
<<Individual>> An instance of an Individual - something with spatio-temporal extent [Grey(80%) R40G40B40] <<Type>> The specification of a Type [Pale Blue R153 G204 B255] <<IndividualType>> The specification of a Type whose members are Individuals [Light Orange R255 G173 B91] <<TupleType>> The specification of a Type whose members are tuples [Light Green R204 G255 B204] <<Powertype>> The specification of a Type that is the set of all subsets of a given Type [Lavender R204 G153 B255] <<Name>> The specification of a name, with the examplar text provided as a tagged value [Tan R255 G254 B153] <<NamingScheme>> The specification of a Type whose members are names [Yellow R255 G255 B0]
The following stereotyped relationships are used in the model:
<<typeInstance>> a relationship between a type and one of its instances (UML:Dependency) [Red R255 G0 B0] <<powertypeInstance>> a relationship between a type and its powerset (UML:Dependency) [Red R255 G0 B0] <<nameTypeInstance>> a relationship between a name and its NameType (UML:Dependency) [Red R255 G0 B0] <<superSubtype>> a relationship between a type and one of its subtypes (UML:Generalisation) [Blue R0 G0 B255] <<wholePart>> a relationship between an individual and one of its parts (UML:Aggregation) [Green R0 G147 B0] <<namedBy>> a relationship between a name and the thing it names [Black R0 G0 B0] <<tuple>>/<<couple> a relationship between a things (UML:n-ary relationship diamond) [Grey(80%) R40G40B40]

A Thing that has spatio-temporal extent.
Note1 - this may be some that existed in the past, exists now, or may exist in some future possible world.
Note2 - the Individual may be scattered - i.e. it is the fusion of several disconnect parts.
Examples:
* Earth * The Eiffel Tower * Me, You * Me and You * France * Sir Isaac Newton

A Powertype is a set of all the subsets of a given Type.
A typeInstance that asserts that the a Type is the Powertype of the type which is the instance. Note: A powertype is the set of all subsets of a given type.

A couple relating two Types which asserts that one type is a subset of the other.
Note - This is the standard super-sub-type relation where the sub-type can either be a proper sub-type or an improper sub-type of the super-type. (An improper sub-type of a type is the type itself. A proper sub-type of a type is not the type itself.) This relation holds between types, where every instance of the sub-type is also an instance of the super-type. Hence the type, Humans, is a sub-type of the type, Animals, because every instance of a Human is also an instance of Animal.
Examples:
* VW Golfs is a subtype of Cars * People over 2m tall is a subtype of People * Types of Pump is a subtype Types of Equipment
The union of Individual, Type, and tuple.

A relationship between two or more things.
Note: Tuples are identified by their places (i.e. the ends of the relationship).
Examples:
* The year 2004 is after the year 2001 * My car is and instance of the type "VW Golfs" * The type "VW Golfs" is a subtype of the type "Cars"

The Powertype of tuple.
Examples:
* wholePart * beforeAfter * typeInstance * superSubtype

A set (or class) of Things.
Note1: Types are identified by their members (i.e. all the things of that type).
Note2: The IDEAS Foundation is a higher-order ontology, so Types may have members that are also Types.
Examples:
* Cars * Volkswagen Beetles * Red Things * Naval Commanders * Ranks

A couple that asserts that a Thing is a member of a Type.
Examples:
* I am a member of the type People (hard to believe, but true) * Field Marshal is of the type Rank * Viscount Bernard Montgomery is of the type Person * The state of Viscount Bernard Montgomery from 1945 to his death is of type Field Marshal

A couple that asserts one (part) Individual is part of another (whole) Individual.
Note - This is the standard whole-part relation where the whole can either be a proper part or an improper part of the part. (An improper part of a whole is the whole itself. Whereas a chocolate chip would be a proper part of a cookie, only the entire cookie is an improper part of itself)
Examples:
* My head is part of Me * January 2004 is part of 2004 * The opening shot of the First World War is part of the First World War * The Border of France is part of France * The Border of France and Belgium is part of the Border of France * The Border of France and Belgium is part of the Border of Belgium

Tuple and Couple are key IDEAS elements. Tuples are n-ary relationships between Things, and couples are binary relationships.
IDEAS defines five subtypes of tuple which each have a fixed set of places. Couple has two places, triple three, quadruple four and quintuple five. See the Tuples Package in Formal Foundation Patterns.

This pattern establishes a relationship between Types and Things where the Thing is an instance of the Type - i.e. class membership
Note that things are instances of types. This means that types may be instances of types - i.e. IDEAS is a higher-order ontology.
This pattern also defines the relationship between a Type and its Powertype. Super-Subtype Pattern

Individuals are those things which have spatio-temporal extent - i.e. physical things that exist now, in the past, or in the future. Individuals are identified by their extent - if two objects occupy precisely the same space at the same time, they are the same. An individual's spatial extent may tend towards zero (e.g. a point in space), as may their temporal extent (e.g. a moment in time at some given location). Individuals may be spatially dissected - e.g. a group of people who are in different locations. Processes are also individuals - their spatial extent being defined by all the participants.
Tuples are relationships between things. For example, the relationship between a car and its wheels is whole-part. Tuples are identified by their places (the things they relate).
Types are sets of things. Types are identified by their extent - the things which belong to the sets. Examples of Types are "Red Things", "Pump Types", "whole-part types", etc.

Formal Foundation Patterns

These are very high-level patterns in the IDEAS model which are necessary for completeness. They are unlikely to be used by the everyday user, but implementers will have to ensure they are implemented in order to get the full ontology capability from IDEAS.

An IndividualType and a SetOfDisjointThings whose instances are types all of whose instances are Individuals and each instance is disjoint, i.e. has no common part.
This mirrors at the mereological level the mathematical notion of disjoint sets - see a DisjointType.
A Type whose instances are types, where for each of them, all their instances are pairwise disjoint.

A SetOfDisjointThings whose instances are Types(i) all of whose instances are Types(ii) where each Type(ii) is disjoint, i.e. has no common instance, from all others.
This corresponds to the mathematical notion of disjoint sets - see a definition below:
Two or more sets which have no elements in common. For example, the sets A = {a,b,c} and B = {d,e,f} are disjoint. (from http://www.mathwords.com/d/disjoint_sets.htm)

In IDEAS, disjointness is defined for Types and Individuals. An instance of SetOfDisjointIndividuals is itself a Type whose members are Individuals that are disjoint (i.e. they have no common parts). An instance of SetOfDisjointTypes is also a Type, but its members are Types that are disjoint (i.e. they share no common instances).
For those unfamiliar with set theory, this will take a bit of getting used to (the examples help).

A WholePartType and an IntersectionOfSetOfOverlappingThings whose instances contain all wholePart couples that link SetOfOverlappingIndividuals with their overlapping parts.

A CoupleType whose instances are couples that link the intersection of a set of Things with its sum.
For more details, see its sub-types: IntersectionOfSetOfOverlappingTypes and IntersectionOfSetOfOverlappingIndividuals
A SuperSubtypeType and an IntersectionOfSetOfOverlappingThings that contains all superSubtype couples that link a SetOfOverlappingTypes with the Types formed by their intersection.
See also:

Intersections are are the sets of relationships that relate overlapping things to their overlaps. An IntersectionOfSetOfOverlappingIndividuals is a set of wholePart relationships relating the overlapping Individuals to the overlap they form (itself also an Individual). An IntersectionOfSetOfOverlappingTypes is a set of superSubtype relationships relating the overlapping Types to the overlap they form (itself also a Type).

The Powertype of RealNumber

A RationalNumber that can be written without a fractional or decimal component.
Example: 65, 7, and −756 are integers; 1.6 and 1 are not integers.
Note: In other terms, integers are the numbers one can count with items such as apples or fingers, and their negatives, as well as 0.
A Type that is a number - i.e. a RealNumber or an Integer

A Type that is a Dedekind cut of the set of rational numbers.
Note: There are different definitions for Real Number in mathematics
A CoupleType whose members are all the couples linking MeasurePoints to RealNumbers. The CoupleType (i.e. the set of couples) represents the scale.

The Property & Measure patterns in IDEAS takes a very simple approach to measureable properties. It uses the representation pattern to give a value to the measure. A given measure can have a number of numeric representations (and text ones for that matter), and these are expressed in terms of a naming or numbering scheme (e.g. the ValueInKilograms, ValueInMetres, etc.).
The pattern shown below is a much more formal approach to measures. For most purposes this is not needed, and really it is only shown for formal completeness and to ensure IDEAS doesn't deviate too far from other 4D extensional ontologies such as ISO15926.
Note that it is by no means clear that ISO15926 has got this right. This is an area of mathematics that is fraught with debate, and this may be far too simplistic an approach. To ensure that IDEAS does not commit to too much in this area that could be wrong, the mapping is only allowed to RealNumbers.

IDEAS provides a simple model for numbers. The model follows the broad consensus in mathematics that numbers are sets (Types) , but does not follow the usual mathematical approach that the specialisation goes from RealNumber to RationalNumber to Integer to PositiveInteger.
Note1: This should not be confused with numerals or other numeric representations. These are the concepts of the numbers themselves, not their representations
Note2: The specialisation hiearchy shown here is by no means accepted by all pure mathematicians and philosophers of mathematics

Overlap : Proper Overlap

When two or more individuals overlap, it is often useful to identify the Individual that is the overlapping part. In IDEAS, this is identified by a Singleton (an instance of SingletonSetOfOverlappingPart) whose only instance is the Individual identified by the overlap.

In IDEAS, overlapping is defined for Types and Individuals. An instance of SetOfOverlappingIndividuals is itself a Type whose members are Individuals that overlap (i.e. they a common part/parts). An instance of SetOfOverlappingTypes is also a Type, but its members are Types that overlap (i.e. they share common instances).
This is a general pattern that is not used very often (Proper Overlap is what most users would require). The reason for this is that the overlaps described on this page include those cases where one thing completely overlaps the other.
Overlapping Part
A SetOfProperOverlappingThings is what most people would intuitively understand to be an overlap, because it excludes the cases where one thing is a completely a part of the other.

Tuple Powertypes

The IDEAS ontology makes a distinction between things and the ways in which they are represented (e.g. their names, identifiers, etc.). This may seem like an obvious distinction, but most software systems do not do this - i.e. they conflate the object and its name.
By separating representation from extent, IDEAS allows any given Thing to have more than one representation. For example, the set of all tables might be called "Table" and also called "Tisch". A given car could be identified both by its VIN number and its manufacturer serial number (note that the vehicle registration number only identifies a state of the vehicle from when it is manufactured to when it is unregistered).
This allows IDEAS to be very precise about the extent of things whilst still allowing a great deal of flexibility in representation.
Couple Powertypes

Three levels of tuple Powertype are provided in IDEAS for convenience. There is no limit to the number of Powertype levels a tuple might have. They all descend from PlaceableType, which is the set of all types which may have places defined.

A powertype is the set of all subsets of a given Type. It is quite easy to confuse a Powertype with Type whose members are Types (a Type of Types). A Powertype is a special Type of Types which consists of all the possible subsets of a given Type.
For example, if we have a Type "Pump", its powertype would be "PumpType". This powertype would consist of all possible types of pump - e.g. "centrifugal pump", "reciprocating pump", "peristaltic pump", "Acme Pumps Model No 1234".
Because the Powertype is the set of all subsets, those can include such Types as "centrifugal pumps and peristaltic pumps", "all pumps that aren't peristaltic", "all blue coloured pumps", etc.
For more information on this subject, see Cantor's Theorem - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantor's_theorem

Singletons, Doubletons, etc.

Singletons are types which have only one member. Doubletons are types which have two members. Tripletons are types which have three members. Quadrupletons are types which have four members. Quintupletons are (not surprisingly) types which have five members.
These Types are intended for re-use across the model. There may be a need for Types which have a greater fixed number of members, and these should be created following this pattern, as required.

A SumOfSetOfThings and a WholePartType whose instances link the fusion of a set of Individuals with its fused whole.
In other words, this relates an IndividualType (a collection of Individuals) to its mereological sum.
See http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mereology/#Sum

A FusionOfSetOfIndividuals whose fusioned Type is a SetOfDisjointIndividuals.
This is a division of a Individual into disjoint parts.

A SumOfSetOfThings whose summed Type is a SetOfDisjointThings.
This is a division of a Thing into disjoint parts/sub-types.

A UnionOfSetOfTypes whose unioned Type is a SetOfDisjointTypes
This is a division of a Type into disjoint subTypes.
See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_a_set and http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_a_set.

A CoupleType whose instances are couples that link the sum of a set of Things with its sum.
For more detail, see its subTypes - UnionOfSetOfTypes and FusionOfSetOfIndividuals.

A SumOfSetOfThings and a SuperSubtypeType whose instances are couples that link the union of a set of Types with these Types.
In other words, this relates a Type (a collection of Types) to its set-theoretic sum (aka union).
Sum, Fusion & Union
The union pattern describes the union of Types or the Fusion of Individuals - i.e. it is used to sum Things.

The partition model brings together the disjoint and union models to build the basis for partition. The principle is that if a thing is partitioned, the partitions must be disjoint, and the union/sum/fusion of the partitions is the Thing that was partitioned.

These are high-level patterns required to support the IDEAS nations own models (e.g. the DoDAF Meta-Model). They provide the semantic anchor points that national models can specialise for their own use.

A couple that asserts one Individual's temporal extent is completely before the temporal extent of another.

beforeAfter is a couple representing temporal sequence - i.e. where one Individual's temporal extent is completely before the temporal extent of another.
When the beforeAfter relationship is used in conjuction with the temporalBoundary pattern (see temporalWholePart), it can be used to express more complex situations such as one individual beginning before another begins, or one ending before another ends.

Intentional Construction

This section of the model covers those objects which have come to have a certain meaning due to the actions of people or other responsible agents. Examples are marriage, countries, money, etc. which only have meaning by the implicit or explicit agreement of responsible agents.
Note that this should not be confused with IntentionalProcess, which is a process conducted by a responsible agent, and is not an IntentionallyConstructedThing.

A Property whose members are Individuals that have a property of being capable to manifest a CategoricalProperty under certain conditions other things being equal. It is critical when describing the disposition to specify the conditions both for the dispositional and the categorical property that is capable of being manifested. These can range from quite stringent conditions, the DispositionalProperty of 'being capable of flying at Mach 2, at a moment's notice' to the more lax, the property of 'being capable of flying at Mach 2, once suitably configured'. Note that these have the same manifestation - the categorical property of 'flying at Mach 2'. Similarly, it is often critical to describe in detail the conditions that apply to the CategoricalProperty that can be manifested, so, for example, 'flying at Mach 2, in good weather'.
Example:
Ability to fly at Mach 2 Ability to strike a target 10km away Ability to dissolve in water

A Property that is always exhibited by its instances (Individuals). Formally, a CategoricalProperty is the set of things that have a property simpliciter without reference to the capability to manifest another property (as is the case with DispositionalProperties (qv.)). So, for example, the property of 'flying at Mach 2' is a CategoricalProperty, whereas 'being capable of flying at Mach 2' is not.
Examples:
10kg 40cm Fitting in an ISO container

A MeasureInstance whose members are Individuals that all have the same electric current flowing through them

Measure are Types. IndividualTypes whose members are all members of a Measure (e.g. all laptops of a certain type weigh 2.23kg) then there exists a superSubtype tuple between them. This tuple is measureOfType and relates an IndividualType to the Measure it is a subtype of.

The measures model in IDEAS is deliberately kept to a minimum. It simply provides a framework for defining measure types, measures and a mechanism for representing a given measure. It also defines a few commonly used measure types such as mass, frequency, length, etc., but an IDEAS implementation can extend this set by simply creating new instances of MeasureType.
The measure model is quite simple. Measures are types - e.g. 2kg is the set of all things that weigh two kilograms. The members of these sets are always individuals. Measures have MeasureTypes - e.g. mass, length, etc. A given measure may have more than one representation. For example, the 2kg measure might be represented as "2.0kg", "2 kilos", "2.2046lbs", etc.
IDEAS does not make any attempt to reconcile units of measure against each other, it simply provides a framework for defining a property, giving it a value, and assigning the property to a thing. IDEAS also provides a few commonly used measures, and their corresponding SI unit.
The other aspect of measures not detailed by this pattern is the detail about precisely what the measure is of. For example, the length of a car can be measured bumper to bumper (fender to fender for our colonial chums), or by its wheelbase. The measure pattern described here is not concerned with precisely what is being classified, so it is up to the user to be precise about what they apply a measure to.
The two main aspects of this measure pattern are shown in the example below. Assigning the measure is actually an assertion that an individual belongs to a set (in this case, the set of things that weight 2kg). Secondly, there is the representation of the measure.

The IDEAS Foundation specifies a few commonly used representations that correspond to the SI Units of Measure - such as kilograms, metres, hertz, etc. These are linked to their equivalent MeasureInstances.

Measure are often ranges (e.g. between 2kg and 2.4kg). As with simple measures, these are Types, and their members are Individuals. IDEAS only species ranges in terms of their upper and lower bound (i.e. not by +/- tolerance, statistic deviation, etc.)

IDEAS takes a very simple approach to representing Measures. The Representation pattern is specialised for NumericMeasureRepresentation. This approach does not claim to be anything more than a naming mechanism for Measures.
Note: Purists would argue that the Measure should first be mapped onto a number which itself should be represented numerically. The set of mappings would then represent the scale - e.g. the kilogram scale - and so give a more detailed representation of units of measure. This does not mean that what is shown here is incorrect - it is just a simplification.

Temporal Whole-Part Pattern

In order to represent change over time, the IDEAS model defines temporal whole parts of individuals. Any number of temporal parts can be recognised for any given element to cover different periods of time. Those periods of time may overlap.

Unique Names
Representation Powertypes
Signs are individual utterances (e.g. a spoken word, a written word, a drawn or printed symbol, etc.) that signify a Thing - i.e. they are uttered in order to refer to something.

The IDEAS Naming Pattern specialises the Representation Pattern to cover those representations which identify Things.
This pattern defines the mechanism for naming objects. Any Thing may have many names. Each name must be defined in context of a NamingScheme, and each name can name only one thing. Names can be numeric or text, but StringName is widely used.
If two Things share the same name, two Name instances would be required in IDEAS.
This pattern is based on P.F.Strawson's theory of description and utterances, and Quine's Roots of Reference.

The IDEAS ontology makes a distinction between things and the ways in which they are represented (e.g. their names, identifiers, etc.). This may seem like an obvious distinction, but most software systems do not do this - i.e. they conflate the object and its name.
By separating representation from extent, IDEAS allows any given Thing to have more than one representation. For example, the set of all tables might be called "Table" and also called "Tisch". A given car could be identified both by its VIN number and its manufacturer serial number (note that the vehicle registration number only identifies a state of the vehicle from when it is manufactured to when it is unregistered).
This allows IDEAS to be very precise about the extent of things whilst still allowing a great deal of flexibility in representation.

The IDEAS Descriptions Pattern specialises the Representation Pattern to cover representations which describe Things. These descriptions could be in any format (e.g. an instance of Description AND IntegerRepresentation), but StringDescription is of particular interest so has been singled out for inclusion.

The Property & Measure patterns in IDEAS takes a very simple approach to measureable properties. It uses the representation pattern to give a value to the measure. A given measure can have a number of numeric representations (and text ones for that matter), and these are expressed in terms of a naming or numbering scheme (e.g. the ValueInKilograms, ValueInMetres, etc.).
The pattern shown below is a much more formal approach to measures. For most purposes this is not needed, and really it is only shown for formal completeness and to ensure IDEAS doesn't deviate too far from other 4D extensional ontologies such as ISO15926.
